“We started off our day in circle. Everyone introduced themselves and as we went around it felt like were really starting to get to know each other, an impressive feat on the first day of school. It really showed the focus Paladin puts on relationship building. It was also just fun. We had a good time playing get to know you games and learning about Paladin together. It was really fun to introduce the students to project based learning and see all of the the ideas they came up with.

I’m really looking forward to continuing to get to know the students and Paladin as a whole.” -Seven, Americorps Promise Fellow

post_text: Thank you Upworks, The Sheridan Story, Lisa & Ken and everyone who helped make this possible. Our staff, students and families are so blessed to have you all apart of our Paladin Family! #paladinstrong #paladinknights
shared_text:
Lisa Bloom Peterson
July 20 at 9:29 PM ·

Does your donation matter? Yes it does!

Today we had the joy of sharing your donations with Paladin Career & Technical High School. This absolutely amazing school lifts up kids that were not excelling in traditional schools. There is a fluctuating percentage of homeless kids at Paladin. In a recent survey of their homeless youth, 100% - that's 100%! - said they felt "supported and cared for and their immediate needs were being met by Paladin". WOW!

Today YOU helped Paladin get food and supplies into the lives of their students and you helped their homeless youth know that people they don't know - CARE ABOUT THEM! :)

As fast as we collect items - they go out. Your donation matters!

If you feel led, I can do a contactless pick up at your house or you can drop off at mine. 612.618.6936

Most needed items: larger size diapers, wipes, pull ups, baby formula and food, anything cleaning, PODS for the washing machine, feminine products, pet food, all toiletries and for food - those things that are easy to make (soup, heat and go food, box food, oatmeal, etc.).

THANK YOU!!! ❤️🙏🏿🙏❤️

post_text:
https://centerforschoolchange.org/2019/07/students-see-value-of-alternative-charter-and-pseo-options/

Fardowso Abdi of the Paladin Career and Technical High School in Blaine, recalls: “When I was in a traditional school, people only saw me for my hijab and I was subjected to harassment. Negative feelings festered inside of me and caused me great mental harm. However, I have realized my calling in life: dealing with implicit bias. During my time here at Paladin, I have changed tremendously. I used to be an angry student and I didn’t know why. Paladin gave me the time and space to understand where my anger was coming from, and having this information about myself has empowered me. I am now embracing my role as an advocate and leader among my peers. This is why alternative school programs are so important.”

#schoolchoice #learnyourway #paladinknights

post_text: What’s a strong body, without a strong mind? #mentalstrength #paladinstrong
shared_text:
Calm
December 10, 2019 at 3:11 PM ·

Calm is teaming up with LeBron James to raise awareness about the importance of mental fitness. LeBron credits meditation, sleep, and a healthy mindset as the keys to his extraordinary achievements and personal happiness.

“As an athlete, there’s a lot of focus on physical fitness. This partnership with Calm is all about mental fitness. It’s something I’ve always prioritized, and it’s just as important to my game, my career, and my life than anything I can do physically. The ability to focus and calibrate everything going on inside your mind is a skill that can be strengthened over time, and Calm helps me do that. Through this partnership, I’m also excited to share that important tool with the youth in my foundation and across the country.”

💙🧠💪Please welcome LeBron to the Calm family! #mentalfitness

Minnesota is offering $325 per child for groceries to families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals but do not receive MFIP or SNAP benefits. Apply by June 30 at www.mn.p-ebt.org. It’s a quick application and takes less than 5 minutes to complete.
If your family already receives SNAP benefits, you will automatically receive P-EBT and do not need to take any further action.

Participating in this program won’t affect public charge.

post_text:
Graduation Thursday! Congratulations to our most recent Paladin Graduate Rikeisha Propps!!! 🎓🎉🙌
.
Words of wisdom to fellow classmates: "Don’t hang with the wrong crowd, loyalty will get you caught up in unnecessary situations. Don’t doubt yourself through hard times, because in the end it’ll all be worth it. Everyone goes through something but dark and hard times don’t last forever. Focus on math, everything else could be project-based depending on how dedicated you are. Get as much math help as you can and take EVERY MATH CLASS THEY OFFER. Hating school isn’t gonna get you anywhere, always have a staff member you can trust and rely on. They really can be helpful and you won’t realize it until the end."
.
#grad2020 #PaladinPride #PaladinStrong #graduatetogether2020

post_text:
Graduation Thursday! Congratulations to our most recent Paladin Graduate Alexander Brueske!!! 🎓🎉🙌
.
Words of wisdom to fellow classmates: “Paladin's main education method, project-based learning, is so open and adaptable. Use this flexibility to earn the credits and hit the targets you need while still learning what YOU want to learn in the way you want to do it. Earn those painful math credits by singing, drawing, dancing, or playing an instrument. Earn those history credits by writing a short skit, constructing a battlefield, or dressing as various historic figures. Have fun while also learning! Trust me on this! I managed to turn Minecraft, of all games, into history credits! Play to your strengths, and you'll graduate in no time."
.
#grad2020 #PaladinPride #PaladinStrong #graduatetogether2020

*Food & Resources Available in Mpls and St Paul*

• Pop-up food pantries daily from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. at Emerson and Broadway Ave in North Minneapolis and at Central and Lexington Ave in St. Paul.

• Pop-up food pantry at Longfellow Park, 35th Street and 36th Avenue, Minneapolis.

• Substance Church has food, toiletries and medical supplies available from 1 p.m. to 5 p.m. at the parking lot next to 101 E. Grant St. by the Minneapolis Convention Center.

• Bethlehem Lutheran in the Midway is distributing food and supplies from noon until 7 p.m. Sunday at 436 Roy St. N. in St. Paul.

See the Hunger Solutions website for additional food sites near you.

Community Space to Process, Listen, + Support 12pm - 1pm, Today, Wednesday 5/27

See your student email to join.

We will be holding space for students and staff to process, listen, and support one another regarding the excessive and inhumane use of force that cost the life of George Floyd. This space is intended to be a brave and safe space for all students and staff wanting to process together.

Students: Know that we are here today and moving forward if you are unable to make this time. We are here to process with you anytime.

Our thoughts, love, and light go out to our community members that are mourning, overwhelmed, and rightfully angry.

Want your own Chromebook? Check this out to see if you qualify.

GET CHROMEBOOKS FOR 75% OFF TO HELP WITH DISTANCE LEARNING

As families and school districts prepare for weeks or perhaps months of distance learning, Minnesota Afterschool Advance (MAA) is here to help! The same tax credit MAA uses to help families pay for afterschool and summer activities can also be used to get 75% off up to $200 of computer hardware, like Chromebooks, per family.

How can MAA help?
MAA can help families purchase Chromebooks at a 75% discount. We do this by using a tool called the K-12 Education Tax Credit.

MAA makes a no-interest advance to you for the 75% covered by the tax credit, and then state dollars automatically repay the advance when you file your taxes at the end of the year. These are extra dollars—you will still get your regular refund.

Limit one per household.

https://mnafterschool.org/chromebooks

MNAFTERSCHOOL.ORG

post_text:
Congratulations to our newest graduate MacKenzie Fodness!!! 🎓✨🎉 Miss you and see you at graduation!

Words of wisdom to her fellow classmates:

Even when things feel really overwhelming and stressful, remind yourself what your end goals are and why you're working so hard. Picture what your future will be like once you graduate! What do you want to do in your future? Holding on to the dreams of my future kept me moving forward. Making to do lists and using a planner really helped me keep organized, but don’t forget to take care of yourself along the way. Be kind to yourself and utilize the supports you have to keep strong during this stressful time. You can do this! Just keep your goals in mind and keep telling yourself it’s possible. Anything you want to do in your future you can. You're smart enough, you're strong enough, you are worthy enough. I’m going to miss all of you at Paladin! -MacKenzie Fodness

post_text:
Happy Friday everyone! We are very proud of all the student engagement this week.

Here are some inspirational words to start the weekend...

When you go out and see the empty streets, the empty stadiums, the empty train platforms, don't say to yourself, "It looks like the end of the world." What you're seeing is love in action. What you're seeing, in that negative space, is how much we do care for each other, for our grandparents, for the immuno-compromised brothers and sisters, for people we will never meet.

People will lose jobs over this. Some will lose their businesses. And some will lose their lives. All the more reason to take a moment, when you're out on your walk, or on your way to the store, or just watching the news, to look into the emptiness and marvel at all of that love.

Let it fill and sustain you. It isn't the end of the world. It is the most remarkable act of global solidarity we may ever witness.
―Paul Williams

post_text:
Dear Paladin Community,

We hope this message finds you well and your family healthy. The COVID-19 global pandemic health crisis has been stressful for us all. Thank you for your continued cooperation and grace as we work to adjust to this change in our daily lives. Governor Walz has ordered school facilities closed through April 30 with hopes to resume May 5th (Executive Order 20-19).

We look forward to connecting with all of our students as we start our distance learning tomorrow Monday, March 30th.

Please see Paladin Update 3/29/20 here:
http://www.paladincareertech.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/3.29.2020-COVID-19-Paladin-Update.pdf

Distance Learning Plan:
You can find our distance learning plan and guiding and principles here or visit our website.
http://www.paladincareertech.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Paladin-Distance-Learning-Plan-Google-Docs.pdf

We’ve got your back: thanks for having ours,

Brandon Wait
Executive Director

Good Morning Paladin-

Paladin staff are currently hard at work contacting each student this morning checking in so we can create care packages for curbside pick up by tomorrow.

If your student does not have a cell phone or access to email, please contact the students SSC first and then school if needed at 763-786-4799.

Care packages may include things like; your Chromebook, charger, books, printed homework, and other educational resource needs.

Student care packages will be available for curbside pick up tomorrow, Tuesday, March 24th from 9:00am - 6:00pm. If you are unable to pick up the care package during this time, please contact your students SSC or call the school.

Stay safe and Be Well!

post_text:
Dear Paladin Community,

We are sure you have heard on the news the need to “flatten the curve” of the COVID-19 pandemic. According to the CDC, the number of cases in the US and Minnesota is continuing to rise. Although we can’t predict when the pandemic will be contained, we can assure you that our Paladin staff is committed to resuming instruction on Monday, March 30. We have been working tirelessly to plan for equitable and quality distance learning.

Please see our latest updates on our website and the latest memo here:
http://www.paladincareertech.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/3.20.2020-COVID-19-Paladin-Update.pdf

We will continue to keep you informed as we navigate COVID-19.

Brandon Wait
Executive Director

Here’s how to get free internet while schools are closed:

To take up Spectrum’s offer:

1. Be a household with a student enrolled in a K-12 school or college

2. Go to https://www.internetessentials.com/ or call 855-846-8376 for English or call 855-765-6995 for Spanish

3. All new customers will receive “a free self-install kit” with no shipping fee

It only takes one person to start a movement. From now to December 27, we're encouraging you to Gift Kindness to others for a chance to win a $1,000 donation to your favorite charity. Whether it’s holding the door open, handwriting a note to a loved one, or paying off a stranger’s layaway, kindness is the gift to give this holiday season. Check out all the details, including contest rules here: https://fal.cn/35vFy
